    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-04-16T11:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-04-16T11:36:00-05:00" n="270"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d270">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.51/574: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hanna</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-04-16T10:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1920—10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 9:52 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>110. Department’s telegram 97, March 30, 4 p.m. The Comptroller of the Mexican
                    Treasury informs the Embassy that despite the desire <pb facs="0327" n="227"
                        xml:id="pg_227"/> of the Mexican Government to resume interest payments on
                    its foreign debt his personal opinion is that no payments can be made this year
                    but that when payments are renewed coupons longest overdue will be paid
                    first.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanna</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
